\section{Introduction}

\lettrine[nindent=0em,lines=3]{W}e want to accurately predict the future. The specific problem I set out to solve is to precisely estimate the modes we will use to travel to and from major American airports. In particular I am specifically interested in modeling how driverless cars would affect this phenomenon over the course of the next 20 years. This paper is about the answering an easier problem that needed to be solved along the way: what are the best ways to predict total passenger traffic (pax) at a modern American airport in the event of a catastrophic event?
This necessitates an estimate terminal side traffic, in particular to understand the ebbs and flows of the trains, cars, and busses bringing passengers and staff to the greatest people transportation hubs that have ever been created, the modern airport. The real motivation is to preempt the onslaught to and great change already undergoing such transportation, and prepare these hubs for the driverless car technology that is going to change the world. Data on the terminal side isn't kept consistently or even well understood. Modes differ greatly between airports – while xxx airport has yyy, zzz airport has aaa. However, data on passenger traffic has all the characteristics that are necessary for a robust forecast analysis. That is the approach we pursue in this whitepaper.

DAdsASD \hyperlink{thesentence}{any sentence} SDAFSDF



